<section class="content">
    <h2>What is Student Data?</h2>
    <p>Student data includes any information collected about a student, such as name, address, age, gender, ethnicity, enrollment details, grade level, attendance, course enrollment, test scores, and grades. Health information, including learning-related diagnoses, medical issues, and disciplinary records, is also protected by student data privacy laws.</p>
    <p class="citation">(Mātauranga Matua, 2021)</p>
    
    <div class="data-type-section">
        <h2>Four Types of Educational Data</h2>
        
        <div class="data-type-card">
            <h3>1. Demographic Information</h3>
            <p>Collecting data on students' age, gender, socioeconomic background, income level, and language proficiency enables educational institutions to identify individual learning requirements.</p>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Age</h4>
                <p><strong>Definition:</strong> A way to track development and determine appropriate grade levels.</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Provides insights into age-related learning patterns and optimal timing for educational interventions.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Gender</h4>
                <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Socially formed identities, duties, and behaviours that go beyond biological sex.</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Affects participation rates in extracurricular activities, STEM/arts stereotypes, and access to opportunities.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Race/Ethnicity</h4>
                <p><strong>Definition:</strong> A social or cultural identity rooted in customs, heritage, or ancestry.</p>
                <p><strong>Effects:</strong> Influences achievement disparities, bias in disciplinary measures, and cultural representation.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Socioeconomic Status</h4>
                <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Students' economic and social position relative to others based on income, education, and occupation.</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Affects access to educational resources, opportunities, and support systems.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Language</h4>
                <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Students' methods of communication, both written and oral, including their first language and fluency in other languages.</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Fluency and understanding skills can affect educational outcomes and access to resources.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Disability Status</h4>
                <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Physical, sensory, mental, or emotional disabilities that affect learning capacity.</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Affects capacity to obtain assistance and accommodations that promote academic achievement.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Geographic Location</h4>
                <p><strong>Definition:</strong> The geographic location of a student's home or town.</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Affects access to educational opportunities and resources, as well as social and cultural factors influencing academic performance.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="data-type-card">
            <h3>2. Academic Performance</h3>
            <p>Data on academic performance quantifies pupils' growth and accomplishments in a variety of areas and skills.</p>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Grades</h4>
                <p>Scores or letters obtained on assignments, tests, and courses indicating understanding and mastery of material.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Standardized Test Scores</h4>
                <p>Results from standardized exams (SAT, ACT, state exams) that compare performance to other students.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Course Completion Rates</h4>
                <p>The percentage of students who finish a course or program, indicating perseverance and success.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Attendance Rates</h4>
                <p>The percentage of time students spend in school or class, indicating involvement and participation.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Graduation Rates</h4>
                <p>The percentage of students that finish their education within a given time frame.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Progress Monitoring Data</h4>
                <p>Information gathered over time to monitor development in specific abilities or domains.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Teacher Observations</h4>
                <p>Qualitative data on student performance in classroom activities, behavior, participation, and assignment completion.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="data-type-card">
            <h3>3. Behavioral Records</h3>
            <p>Information on students' behavior both within and outside of the classroom.</p>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Discipline Incidents</h4>
                <p>Information on student offenses and disciplinary procedures taken.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Suspensions and Expulsions</h4>
                <p>The number of times a student has been removed from school due to behavioral issues.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Behavior Checklists</h4>
                <p>Standardized checklists for documenting student behavior.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Peer and Parent Surveys</h4>
                <p>Documentations of student behavior provided by classmates or parents.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Counselling and Mental Health Records</h4>
                <p>Qualitative records of counselling or mental health appointments.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="data-type-card">
            <h3>4. Engagement Indicators</h3>
            <p>Information about how students are engaged in learning activities.</p>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Class Participation</h4>
                <p>The extent to which students take part in class activities and discussions.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Homework Completion</h4>
                <p>The quantity of student work completed outside of class.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Learning Time</h4>
                <p>Time that students spend on learning activities.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Performance on Assessments</h4>
                <p>The extent to which students show knowledge and ability in coursework.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Technology Use</h4>
                <p>How students leverage technologies to assist their studying.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Extracurricular Involvement</h4>
                <p>Participation in school organizations, clubs, sports, and other activities.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Social and Emotional Learning</h4>
                <p>Development of social and emotional skills like self-awareness and relationship skills.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="data-point">
                <h4>Mobility Rates</h4>
                <p>Student rate of switching schools over time.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <h2>How Data is Used: From Personalized Learning to Institutional Analytics</h2>
    <p>Big Data Analytics (BDA) in education serves dual purposes: improving individual student outcomes and streamlining institutional processes.</p>
    <p class="citation">(Palani, 2024)</p>
    
    <div class="card-container">
