<section class="content">
    <h2>Student Privacy Laws: What District & School Administrators Need To Know</h2>
    <p>Due to the increased use of technology in schools, student data privacy has become a major concern. Education officials need to navigate complicated federal, state, and local privacy rules.</p>
    <p class="citation">(Education Framework, 2025)</p>
    
    <div class="law-section">
        <h2>Why Should Schools Care About Data Protection?</h2>
        <p>Schools handle vast amounts of sensitive student data, exposing them to strict legal regulations. The consequences of failing to uphold these standards can be severe, as demonstrated when Lincoln College in Illinois had to shut down permanently following a ransomware attack on its data systems in 2022.</p>
        <p class="citation">(Nason, 2024)</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="law-section">
        <h2>The Big Three Privacy Laws for Student Data</h2>
        
        <div class="law-card">
            <h3>FERPA (Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act)</h3>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>What is it?</h4>
                <p>FERPA, created in 1974 by the U.S. Department of Education, is a federal statute that gives parents and students aged 18 and above the right to examine educational records. It applies to both paper and electronic documents.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>How it works:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Applies exclusively to education records maintained by educational institutions</li>
                    <li>Prohibits disclosure of personally identifiable information without consent</li>
                    <li>Includes exceptions for school officials, directory information, and emergencies</li>
                    <li>Gives parents and students control over their educational records</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>Why it's important:</h4>
                <p>FERPA is the cornerstone statute protecting student data privacy in the United States. It empowers students and ensures a secure learning environment by balancing privacy rights with institutional needs.</p>
                <p class="citation">(Frank & Wagner, 2018; Sayer & M, 2005)</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>Common Myths vs. The Truth</h4>
                <table class="myth-truth-table">
                    <tr>
                        <th>Myth (What People Think)</th>
                        <th>Truth (How it Actually Works)</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>FERPA protects all student information</td>
                        <td>It protects only "education records," not personal knowledge or observations</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>FERPA prohibits the release of anything to parents</td>
                        <td>Schools may release information to parents of tax dependents or in health/safety emergencies</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Violating FERPA is catastrophic</td>
                        <td>The penalty (revocation of federal funding) has never been exercised</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                <p class="citation">(MCDONALD, 2008)</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>Current Challenges:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Misunderstanding and "myth-perpetuation" among staff</li>
                    <li>Adapting a 1974 law to digital technology and cloud storage</li>
                    <li>Ensuring data security in an era of frequent breaches</li>
                    <li>Faculty using apps without proper vetting of terms of service</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="citation">(Kelly & Hailly, 2018)</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="law-card">
            <h3>COPPA (Children's Online Privacy Protection Act)</h3>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>What is it?</h4>
                <p>COPPA was implemented in 1998 by the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) to protect children under the age of 13 online privacy. It requires verifiable parental consent before collecting personal information from children.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>How it works in education:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Schools can act as parents' agents for educational purposes</li>
                    <li>Consent is valid only for educational purposes, not commercial use</li>
                    <li>Regulates website and online service operators, not schools directly</li>
                    <li>Requires operators to provide clear privacy policies and security</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="citation">(S. Skowronski, 2022)</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>Why it's important:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Children are vulnerable and may not understand privacy risks</li>
                    <li>Protects against targeting, exploitation, and real-world harms</li>
                    <li>Essential with the massive shift to online learning</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="citation">(A. Matecki, 2010)</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>Current Challenges:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>School exception undermines parental consent purpose</li>
                    <li>Third-party trackers in educational services</li>
                    <li>Weak enforcement and "slap on the wrist" penalties</li>
                    <li>Age limitation leaves teenagers unprotected</li>
                    <li>Inadequate teacher awareness of requirements</li>
                    <li>Struggles to keep pace with technological change</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="citation">(Herold, 2017)</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="law-card">
            <h3>GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation)</h3>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>What is it?</h4>
                <p>The GDPR is a comprehensive European Union law that came into force in May 2018 to protect the privacy and personal information of EU residents. It implements stringent requirements for data collection, processing, and protection.</p>
                <p class="citation">(BRIEFING, 2018; University of california, 2018)</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>Key principles:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Lawfulness, transparency, and data minimization</li>
                    <li>Rights to access, rectification, and erasure of data</li>
                    <li>Accountability and security requirements</li>
                    <li>Unifies data privacy law throughout Europe</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="law-point">
                <h4>Relevance to education:</h4>
                <p>The GDPR is particularly important for protecting vulnerable teenage learners as schools adopt digital technologies and AI-based tools like Learning Analytics (LA).</p>
                <p class="citation">(Paludi, 2024; Bećirović, 2023)</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="case-study">
        <h3>Case Study: University discloses student's location to Police</h3>
        <p>In 2008, a New Zealand university disclosed a student's examination details to police due to mental health concerns about the student's firearms license. This case highlights the balance between privacy and safety concerns in educational settings.</p>
    </div>
